EAI Tutorial 3.3

Data Wrangling

Data wrangling is a process of reorganizing, transforming and re-mapping data from one “raw” form into another in order to make it more usable and valuable for a variety of downstream applications. For rectangular data, data wrangling is commonly handled in R by Tidyverse packages tidyr and dplyr.

Data Frames

In R and Python, multivariate cross-sectional data — i.e. data in which each column is a variable/attribute/feature, and each row is an observation are represented by arrays, matrices, tables, data frames and tibbles . There are two flavors of rectangular data, differing mostly in the jargon used to name columns and rows.

Long data have the number of rows (observations) usually higher than the number of columns (attributes/variables) and in the wide data the arrangement is the other way around. In this tutorial, you will be dealing with long data.

Dplyr: Grammar of DF Manipulation

dplyr implements a grammar of data manipulation, providing a consistent set of verbs that solve common rectangular data manipulation challenges. The following core functions are implemented to manipulate existing rows (observation), columns (variables), or aggregate existing data into new rows and columns.

Extracting Variables with select()

It is not uncommon to get data sets like players_22.csv with hundreds or even thousands of variables. select() allows us to rapidly zoom in on selected slices of data after providing the names of the variables. To work with less data on next iterations, we can select the appropriate columns like this:

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob,
                skill_moves, skill_dribbling, skill_curve, 
                skill_fk_accuracy, skill_long_passing, skill_ball_control) %>% 
  print(n=3)
## # A tibble: 19,239 × 8
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 L. Messi          1987-06-24           4              96          93
## 2 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4              85          79
## 3 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5              88          81
## # ℹ 19,236 more rows
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>

A R code above selects seven player’s attributes our of 100, containing player’s name, date of birth, and every column starting with skill. It keeps all rows, however.

Including every skill columns into select() is tedious. Instead, it’s more convenient to combine helper functions together with select(). For example, you can add additional columns using regex matching for which rules can be defined. Some examples how this works are show below:

The way to think about select() is that that expression eventually evaluates to a logical vector. So if you use starts_with() it goes through the variables and asks which names start with the right set of characters.

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>% 
          print(n=3)
## # A tibble: 19,239 × 8
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 L. Messi          1987-06-24           4              96          93
## 2 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4              85          79
## 3 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5              88          81
## # ℹ 19,236 more rows
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>

Similarly, you can use where(), which takes a function and returns all variables for which the function returns TRUE.

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob, where(is.numeric)) %>%

Extracting Variables with .

Square bracket [ subsetting is handy, but it can be cumbersome and difficult to read, especially for complicated operations. select(), on the other hand, is plainly understood. The downside is that it does not allow customizing object type on return.

This causes problems on the ML end because these functions need vector(s) as their input.

Say, you want to extract a single column of a data frame as an atomic vector. Subsetting the original data frame with select() leads to preserving subsetting.

To extract an atomic vector from a data frame, use the . operator together with the $ sign operator. A viable alternative is pull(). Both options will do simplifying subsetting.

 typeof(data %>% .$skill_dribbling) # This code extracts numeric vector of dribbling values.
## [1] "double"

Extracting Observations with filter()

filter() allows you to select observations based on their values. For example, let’s takte the FIFA22 data and select players with dribbling skill above average with following code:

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(skill_dribbling > mean(data$skill_dribbling)) %>%
  print(n=5)
## # A tibble: 12,643 × 8
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 L. Messi          1987-06-24           4              96          93
## 2 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4              85          79
## 3 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5              88          81
## 4 Neymar Jr         1992-02-05           5              95          88
## 5 K. De Bruyne      1991-06-28           4              88          85
## # ℹ 12,638 more rows
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>

You can combine multiple filter() parameters with “& (and)” and “| (or)”, representing logical AND and logical OR.

The %in% Operator

If the number of observations for selection is small, a useful shorthand exists as x %in% y. The %in% operator will select every row in a data frame where x is one of the values in y. For example, you can select the first three players by listing their names.

data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  print(n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4              85          79
## 2 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5              88          81
## 3 Neymar Jr         1992-02-05           5              95          88
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>

Data Frame Operations

Column Modification with mutate()

mutate() is a function for creating new variables from existing ones. If you want to keep only the new column and discard all other columns, use transmute().

Creating a New Column

For example, let’s mean-normalize skill_dribbling values and append normalized values as a new column.

Mean-normalized values are normally refereed to as the relative values and as such, they are suited for interpretation. ML guys generally love relative values. The original values are often refereed to as absolute values.

Notice that the new column will be appended at the end of a data frame.

data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  filter(skill_dribbling > mean(data$skill_dribbling)) %>%
  mutate(normalized_SD = skill_dribbling - mean(data$skill_dribbling))
## # A tibble: 3 × 9
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4              85          79
## 2 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5              88          81
## 3 Neymar Jr         1992-02-05           5              95          88
## # ℹ 4 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>, normalized_SD <dbl>

Modifying an Existing Column

You can also modify existing columns as shown on a last line of the following code. In that case, the modified column is not moved away from its original position.

data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  filter(skill_dribbling > mean(data$skill_dribbling)) %>%
  mutate(skill_dribbling = skill_dribbling - mean(data$skill_dribbling))
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4            29.3          79
## 2 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5            32.3          81
## 3 Neymar Jr         1992-02-05           5            39.3          88
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>

Modifying Multiple Columns with across()

across() makes it easy to transform multiple columns. This is one of helper functions that work only inside inside in “data-masking” functions like summarise() and mutate().

data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%   
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), as.integer))
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   short_name        dob        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>           <int>           <int>       <int>
## 1 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21           4              85          79
## 2 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05           5              88          81
## 3 Neymar Jr         1992-02-05           5              95          88
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <int>, skill_long_passing <int>,
## #   skill_ball_control <int>

Renaming Columns with rename()

rename() changes the column name to a new value.

data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  rename(date_of_birth = dob)
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   short_name        date_of_birth skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve
##   <chr>             <date>              <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 R. Lewandowski    1988-08-21              4              85          79
## 2 Cristiano Ronaldo 1985-02-05              5              88          81
## 3 Neymar Jr         1992-02-05              5              95          88
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_fk_accuracy <dbl>, skill_long_passing <dbl>,
## #   skill_ball_control <dbl>

Rearrange Columns with relocate()

relocate() offers a very intuitive way to arrange columns. You only need to specify columns to be moved and their new position with either .before= or .after=. relocate() is a shorthand for select(), meaning that everything that can be done with relocate() can be done with select().

data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  relocate(starts_with("skill"), .after = short_name)
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   short_name        skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve skill_fk_accuracy
##   <chr>                   <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>             <dbl>
## 1 R. Lewandowski              4              85          79                85
## 2 Cristiano Ronaldo           5              88          81                84
## 3 Neymar Jr                   5              95          88                87
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_long_passing <dbl>, skill_ball_control <dbl>,
## #   dob <date>
data %>%
  select(short_name, dob, starts_with("skill")) %>%
  filter(short_name %in% c("R. Lewandowski", "Cristiano Ronaldo", "Neymar Jr")) %>%
  relocate(where(is.numeric), .before = where(is.character))
## # A tibble: 3 × 8
##   skill_moves skill_dribbling skill_curve skill_fk_accuracy skill_long_passing
##         <dbl>           <dbl>       <dbl>             <dbl>              <dbl>
## 1           4              85          79                85                 70
## 2           5              88          81                84                 77
## 3           5              95          88                87                 81
## # ℹ 3 more variables: skill_ball_control <dbl>, short_name <chr>, dob <date>

Insert Rows with add_rows()

Tibbles and data frames work reasonably well with rbind() and cbind() functions, which insert one or more rows at the end of the data frame.

You can also get the same thing done with functions such as add_row() and rows_inset(). The row length of the original and inserted data frames must be the same.

tmp <- data %>% 
  select(short_name, value_eur) %>% 
  filter(short_name == "L. Messi")

tmp %>% add_row(short_name = "P. Belej", value_eur = 10000)
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   short_name value_eur
##   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 L. Messi    78000000
## 2 P. Belej       10000

Aggregate Summary Reports

Data aggregation is a process whereby data is gathered and expressed in a summary form. When data is aggregated, rows and columns are replaced with summary statistics (such as totals, means, standard deviation…).

The original table ceases to exist. Instead, a smaller table is generated which can be pivoted, transformed and summarized again.

Summary Statistics with summarise()

In R, summary statistics are generated with the summarise() function. summarise() can be cumbersome function to use because it requires you to enumerate every statistic you use for every variable.

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob, skill_dribbling) %>%
  summarise(mean_dribbling = mean(skill_dribbling),
            min_dribbling = min(skill_dribbling),
            max_dribbling = max(skill_dribbling),
            number_of_records = n())
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##   mean_dribbling min_dribbling max_dribbling number_of_records
##            <dbl>         <dbl>         <dbl>             <int>
## 1           55.7             4            96             19239
# n() is a shorthand function for number of rows. 
# tally() does the same thing, but also works outside summarise().

A viable alternative are listed-functions and functionals, such as map().

Data Aggregation with group_by()

Summary statistics are often not calculated on the whole dataset, but on groups (e.g. player’s position: goal keeper, forward, center, …). group_by() uses that information to break down an existing table into groups of nested data frames, on which operations are performed. The resulting compuations are then aggregated into a table or a list.

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob, league_level, skill_dribbling) %>%
  group_by(league_level) %>% 
  summarise(mean_dribbling = mean(skill_dribbling),
            min_dribbling = min(skill_dribbling),
            max_dribbling = max(skill_dribbling),
            number_of_records = n())

The resulting summary statistics are aggregated into a new data frame, which replaces the original data. Here, you can see the outline of steps leading to summary stats of players from different league levels.

## # A tibble: 6 × 5
##   league_level mean_dribbling min_dribbling max_dribbling number_of_records
##          <dbl>          <dbl>         <dbl>         <dbl>             <int>
## 1            1           56.0             4            96             14857
## 2            2           56.1             5            85              2513
## 3            3           52.8             4            75              1168
## 4            4           51.5             5            71               613
## 5            5           48.9             5            65                27
## 6           NA           55.4             7            78                61

Ordering rows with arrange()

arrange() orders the rows of a data frame by the values of selected columns.

Unlike other dplyr verbs, arrange() largely ignores grouping; you need to explicitly mention grouping variables (or use .by_group = TRUE) in order to group by them, and functions of variables are evaluated once per data frame, not once per group. Use desc() for arrangement in a descending order.

data %>% 
  select(short_name, dob, league_level, skill_dribbling) %>%
  arrange(desc(skill_dribbling))
## # A tibble: 19,239 × 4
